"Muñoz I., Feral J., Ayllón J.A., Malato S., Martin M.J., Perrot J.Y., Vincent M., Domènech X.","Life-cycle assessment of a coupled advanced oxidation-biological process for wastewater treatment: Comparison with granular activated carbon adsorption",2007,"Environmental Engineering Science","24","5",,"638","651",,,10.1089/ees.2006.0134,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34248637308&partnerID=40&md5=5ba01e6bda9bdba186de4eee135ce8e9","Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain; Plataforma Solar de Almería-CIEMAT, Carretera Senés km 4, Almería, Spain; Laboratori d'Enginyeria Química I Ambiental (LEQUIA), Universitat de Girona, Girona, Spain; Trailigaz, Garges-lès-Gonesse Cedex, France; Ecosystem Environmental Services, St. Andreu de Llavaneres, Barcelona, Spain; Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain","Muñoz, I., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain, Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra, Barcelona, Spain; Feral, J., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain; Ayllón, J.A., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain; Malato, S., Plataforma Solar de Almería-CIEMAT, Carretera Senés km 4, Almería, Spain; Martin, M.J., Laboratori d'Enginyeria Química I Ambiental (LEQUIA), Universitat de Girona, Girona, Spain; Perrot, J.Y., Trailigaz, Garges-lès-Gonesse Cedex, France; Vincent, M., Ecosystem Environmental Services, St. Andreu de Llavaneres, Barcelona, Spain; Domènech, X., Departament de Química, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Barcelona, Spain","A comparative Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) concerning two strategies for coupling advanced oxidation processes (AOPs) with biological treatment, namely solar-driven photo-Fenton and ozonation, is performed. In addition, these emergent technologies are compared to a reference technology, namely granular activated carbon (GAC) adsorption. The study is based on pilot plant and laboratory tests using alphamethyl-phenylglycine (MPG) as a target substance. The system under study includes production of infrastructure for the solar plant, chemicals, electricity, transport of all these materials to the plant site, management of the spent catalyst by landfilling and spent GAC by regeneration, as well as treatment of the obtained effluent in a conventional municipal wastewater treatment plant (MWWTP) and excess sludge treatment by incineration. Nine environmental impact categories are included in the LCA: global warming, ozone depletion, human toxicity, freshwater aquatic toxicity, photochemical ozone formation, acidification, eutrophication, energy consumption, and land use. The experimental results obtained in the pilot plant show that both AOPs are able to obtain a biodegradable effluent, while GAC is able to adsorb almost 100% MPG. The results of the LCA show that none of the treatment options appears as preferable at the same time in all nine impact indicators. Nevertheless, in six of these indicators solar-driven photo-Fenton coupled to biological treatment obtains the lowest impact. From a weighted life cycle impact assessment (LCIA) results perspective, solar-driven photo-Fenton appears as the most environmentally friendly alternative, even in locations with relatively low solar resources. © Mary Ann Liebert, Inc.","Activated carbon; Biological coupling; Life cycle assessment (LCA); Ozone; Photo-Fenton; Solar energy; Wastewater treatment","Biological coupling; Biological treatment; Granular activated carbon (GAC); Life Cycle Assessment (LCA); Activated carbon; Adsorption; Bioactivity; Life cycle; Oxidation; Ozone; Ozonization; Solar energy; Wastewater treatment; alpha methylphenylglycine; carbon; glycine derivative; ozone; unclassified drug; acidification; adsorption; article; biotransformation; comparative study; effluent; electricity; energy consumption; eutrophication; greenhouse effect; incineration; laboratory test; land use; landfill; life cycle assessment; oxidation; ozonation; sludge; solar energy; toxicity; waste water management; water contamination",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"ANDREOZZI, R., CAPRIO, V., INSOLA, A., MAROTTA, R., Advanced oxidation processes (AOP) for water purification and recovery (1999) Catalysis Today, 53, p. 51; AZAPAGIC, A., CLIFT, R., Life cycle assessment and multiobjective optimisation (1999) J. Cleaner Product, 7, p. 135; BAUER, R., FALLMANN, H., The photo-Fenton oxidation. A cheap and efficient wastewater treatment method (1997) Res. Chem. Intermediates, 23, p. 291; BAYER, P., HEDER, E., KARL, U., FINKEL, M., Economical and ecological comparison of granular activated carbon (GAC) adsorbers refill strategies (2005) Water Res, 39, p. 1719; BLANCO, J., MALATO, S., (2003) Solar detoxification, , France: UNESCO Publishing; CONSOLI, F., ALLEN, D., BOUSTEAD, I., DE OUDE, N., FAVA, J., FRANKLIN, W., QUAY, B., POSTLETHWATTE, D., (1993) Guidelines for Life-Cycle Assessment: A Code of Practice, , Brussels, Belgium: Society of Environmental Toxicology and Chemistry. Belgium; DOKA, G. (2003). Life Cycle Inventories of Waste Treatment Services. Final report ecoinvent 2000 No. 13, EMPA St. Gallen. Duebendorf, Switzerland: Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories(2005) Integrated Pollution Prevention and Control. Reference Document on Economics and Cross-media Effects, , EIPPCB European Integrated Pollution Prevention and Control Bureau, Seville, Spain: European Commission European IPPC Bureau; (1996) Council Directive 96/61/EC of 24 September 1996 concerning integrated pollution prevention and control, p. 26. , 10/10/1996; EU. (2000). Directive 2000/60/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council establishing a framework for the Community action in the field of water policy. Official Journal L 327, 22/12/2000, 0001EU. (2001). Decision No 2455/2001/EC of the European Parliam